{"questionId":"9076097","questionHtml":"<p>Two pure samples of radioactive nuclides X and Y have the same initial number of atoms. The half-life of X is&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{T_{\\frac{1}{2}}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>T</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mfrac>\n          <mn>1</mn>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </mfrac>\n      </mrow>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p>After a time equal to 4 half-lives of X the ratio&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{{\\text{number of atoms of X}}}}{{{\\text{number of atoms of Y}}}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>number of atoms of X</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>number of atoms of Y</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> is&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{1}{8}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mn>8</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p>What is the half-life of Y?</p>\n<p>A.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.25{T_{\\frac{1}{2}}}\">\n  <mn>0.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>T</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mfrac>\n          <mn>1</mn>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </mfrac>\n      </mrow>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.5{T_{\\frac{1}{2}}}\">\n  <mn>0.5</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>T</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mfrac>\n          <mn>1</mn>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </mfrac>\n      </mrow>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"3{T_{\\frac{1}{2}}}\">\n  <mn>3</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>T</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mfrac>\n          <mn>1</mn>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </mfrac>\n      </mrow>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4{T_{\\frac{1}{2}}}\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>T</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mfrac>\n          <mn>1</mn>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </mfrac>\n      </mrow>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>D</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9076097","referenceCode":"18M.1.SL.TZ1.26","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Two pure samples of radioactive nuclides X and Y have the same initial number of atoms. The half-life of X is T 1 2 . After a time equal to 4 half-lives of X the ratio number of at","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"26","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 7: Atomic, nuclear and particle physics","7.1 – Discrete energy and radioactivity","Core","Topic 7: Atomic, nuclear and particle physics"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}